{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17476795","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17476795"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T22:51:42+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T22:51:42+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13951"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13951","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13951"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.07,0.48,0.18,0.19,0.09]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6581"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"49926"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6581","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6581"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13951"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"35184"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"13"},{"type":"tags","id":"39"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1177"},{"type":"tags","id":"1643"},{"type":"tags","id":"1753"},{"type":"tags","id":"2108"},{"type":"tags","id":"2316"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"13284"},{"type":"contributions","id":"16178"},{"type":"contributions","id":"18655"},{"type":"contributions","id":"38820"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"49926","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/49926"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA two-year-old boy presents to the General Practice clinic with his mother due to recurrent infections. He has a history of eczema since infancy and has been hospitalised twice for pneumonia. His mother reports that he bruises easily. He has no other significant medical history, takes no regular medications and is up to date with immunisations. On examination, he appears pale with scattered petechiae on his arms and legs. His vital signs are within normal limits. Investigations show a platelet count of 30 \u00a0x10\u003Csup\u003E9\u003C/sup\u003E /L (150-400).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Chronic granulomatous disease","Wiskott-Aldrich syndrome","Severe combined immunodeficiency","X-linked agammaglobulinemia","DiGeorge syndrome"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe clinical presentation described is highly suggestive of \u003Cstrong\u003EWiskott-Aldrich syndrome (WAS)\u003C/strong\u003E. This rare X-linked recessive disorder is characterised by the triad of eczema, thrombocytopenia, and recurrent infections. The patient\u0027s history of eczema since infancy, recurrent infections (including hospitalisations for pneumonia), and thrombocytopenia (as evidenced by easy bruising, petechiae, and low platelet count) are all consistent with this diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESevere combined immunodeficiency (SCID)\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents earlier in infancy with failure to thrive and severe, life-threatening infections. While recurrent infections are a feature, SCID does not typically involve eczema or thrombocytopenia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EChronic granulomatous disease (CGD)\u003C/strong\u003E is characterised by recurrent bacterial and fungal infections, particularly those involving the lungs, skin, and lymph nodes. However, CGD does not typically cause thrombocytopenia or eczema.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EX-linked agammaglobulinemia\u003C/strong\u003E presents with recurrent bacterial infections, typically after six months of age when maternal antibodies have waned. These patients have very low or absent B cells and immunoglobulins but do not typically have eczema or thrombocytopenia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDiGeorge syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E is associated with cardiac defects, characteristic facial features, hypocalcaemia, and T-cell deficiency. While infections can occur, the combination of eczema and thrombocytopenia is not typical of this condition.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EManagement of Wiskott-Aldrich syndrome typically includes prophylactic antibiotics to prevent infections, immunoglobulin replacement therapy, and careful management of eczema. Definitive treatment is haematopoietic stem cell transplantation, which can be curative if performed early in life.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Wiskott-Aldrich syndrome is characterized by the triad of eczema, thrombocytopenia, and recurrent infections.","Wiskott-Aldrich syndrome is an X-linked recessive disorder caused by mutations in the WAS gene.","Management of Wiskott-Aldrich syndrome includes prophylactic antibiotics, immunoglobulin replacement, and hematopoietic stem cell transplantation."],"references":["Roberts I. Nelson\u2019s textbook of pediatrics (20th edn.), by Kliegman R, Stanton B, St. Geme J, Schor N (eds). 2017:1364\u20131365 Available at: https://doi.org/10.1007/s00247-017-3907-9","Buchbinder D, Nugent DJ, Fillipovich AH. Wiskott-Aldrich syndrome: diagnosis, current management, and emerging treatments. Appl Clin Genet. 2014 Apr 3;7:55-66. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC4012343/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"35184"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13951"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"35184","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/35184"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-08-04T17:25:24+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-09T09:25:04+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"t